06106nam a22008415i 9780857456892DE-B159720221107062033.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221107t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574568927 a10.1515/97808574568922doi  a(DE-B1597)636742  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHM753b.I354 2009 7aSOC0190002bisacsh04a305.822200aIdentity Matters :bEthnic and Sectarian Conflict /ced. by James L. Peacock, Patricia M. Thornton, Patrick B. Inman. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (258 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIntroduction: Identity Matters -- t1. Ethnic Conflict and Civic Nationalism: A Model -- t2. Social Identity Matters: Predicting Prejudice and Violence in Western Europe -- t3. Readiness to Fight in Crimea: How It Interrelates with National and Ethnic Identities -- t4. Ethnic Identities of the Karen Peoples in Burma and Thailand -- t5. European Attitudes toward Immigrants -- t6. Tibetan Identity in Today’s China -- t7. Cross-Cutting Identities in Singapore: Crabgrass on the Padang -- t8. The Casamance Separatist Conflict: From Identity to the Trap of “Identitism” -- t9. Manufacturing Sectarian Divides: The Chinese State, Identities, and Collective Violence -- t10. Islam and the West: A Perspective from Pakistan -- tConclusion: Ethnic and Sectarian as Ideal Types -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn response to the attacks of September 11, 2001 and war in Afghanistan, the Fulbright New Century Scholars program brought together social scientists from around the world to study sectarian, ethnic, and cultural conflict within and across national borders. As one result of their year of intense discussion, this book examines the roots of collective violence — and the measures taken to avoid it — in Burma (Myanmar), China, Germany, Pakistan, Senegal, Singapore, Thailand, Tibet, Ukraine, Southeast Asia, and Western Europe. Case studies and theoretical essays introduce the basic principles necessary to identify and explain the symbols and practices each unique human group holds sacred or inalienable. The authors apply the methods of political science, social psychology, anthropology, journalism, and educational research. They build on the insights of Gordon Allport, Charles Taylor, and Max Weber to describe and analyze the patterns of behavior that social groups worldwide use to maintain their identities. Written to inform the general reader and communicate across disciplinary boundaries, this important and timely volume demonstrates ways of understanding, predicting and coping with ethnic and sectarian violence. Contributors: Badeng Nima, David Brown, Kwanchewan Buadaeng, Patrick B. Inman, Karina V. Korostelina, James L. Peacock, Thomas F. Pettigrew, Wee Teng Soh, Hamadou Tidiane Sy, Patricia M. Thornton, Mohammad Waseem.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aCollective behavior. 0aEthnic conflict. 0aGroup identity. 0aSocial conflict. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aBrown, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuadaeng, Kwanchewan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInman, Patrick B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInman, Patrick B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKorostelina, Karina V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNima, Badeng, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeacock, James L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 